The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

NATION BRIEFS

 New Delhi, Feb. 25 (PTI) The Supreme Court has held that mental harassment caused by a wife is sufficient cause for the husband to seek divorce.

 Physical violence is not absolutely essential to constitute cruelty and a consistent course of conduct inflicting immeasurable mental agony and torture may well constitute cruelty within the meaning of Section 10 of the act, Justices Arijit Pasayat and Dalveer Bhandari said while dismissing an appeal by a woman challenging a divorce granted by a trial court.

 Islamabad (PTI): Pakistan and India are set for co-operation in education, which could begin with an exchange of books between NCERT and Pakistans National Book Foundation. There is a possibility that the two countries will share expertise and experience in the fields of elementary, secondary and adult education.

 Bhopal (PTI): Survivors of the 1984 Bhopal gas tragedy have sought a monthly pension and free treatment for their children, claiming that chromosomal aberrations among people exposed to the toxic gases have caused birth defects. 

 Thiruvananthapuram (PTI): Eminent Malayalam poet P. Bhaskaran died at his residence on Sunday. He was 83 and is survived by his wife and four children.

 Mumbai (PTI): Bombay High Court has upheld a lower courts decision to acquit 11 accused in a murder case while discounting the testimony of two prosecution witnesses because they had been indicted in the murder of the father of one of the accused. 

 New Delhi (PTI): Director and actor Deepak Tijori, accused in a cheque-bouncing case, has been granted bail by a city court. A city film financier had complained that Tijoris cheque of Rs 15 lakh had bounced.




